I see that as a feature. You might call it "digital localism". You're talking about centralizing categorization of content. Who does that? How do you know you can trust them? Subscribing to mute lists puts the user in control of what he sees. Clients shouldn't do that automatically for you except in the most obvious cases.

I can see how this would result in echo chambers, but isn't that up to the user? If they want to escape, they can always change their preferences. Also, not everyone is interested in joining the "public forum", some people just want to hang out with their friends. Anyway, there is no "public forum", because no one owes you their attention. There are only "public fora", which will always be delineated along ideological lines.

I don't see any real solutions here, only complaining. Feel free to propose one.
